{
    "level": "A1–A2",
    "intro": "In this topic, you will quickly practise <strong>am / is / are</strong>, negatives, short questions, and the patterns <strong>there is / there are</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "Present Forms",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "Start with <strong>am / is / are</strong> in simple sentences.",
            "example": "I am late. / She is ready. / They are here."
        },
        {
            "label": "Questions",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "With <strong>to be</strong>, questions do not use <strong>do / does</strong>.",
            "example": "Are you ready? / Is he at home?"
        },
        {
            "label": "There Is / Are",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "Then practise the patterns for saying what exists in a place.",
            "example": "There is a book on the table."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Starter set",
    "intro": "This subsection moves from the simplest forms to basic questions and there-patterns.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "A1",
            "title": "Present Forms",
            "subtitle": "am / is / are in short affirmative sentences."
        },
        {
            "label": "A1",
            "title": "Negatives",
            "subtitle": "am not, is not, are not, and common short forms."
        },
        {
            "label": "A1",
            "title": "Questions and Short Answers",
            "subtitle": "Am I...?, Is he...?, Are they...? and short answers."
        },
        {
            "label": "A1–A2",
            "title": "There Is / There Are",
            "subtitle": "How to say what is or is not in a place."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. What you will practise",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "am / is / are",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "You will see which form goes with <strong>I</strong>, <strong>he / she / it</strong>, and <strong>you / we / they</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I am tired. / She is a student. / They are at work.",
                    "ua": "Core models for state, identity, and place."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "not and questions",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "You will learn to put <strong>not</strong> after to be and move the form <strong>before the subject</strong> in questions.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "He is not busy. / Are they ready?",
                    "ua": "Negatives and questions without an extra auxiliary."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "There is / There are",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "You will say what is or is not in a room, a house, a bag, or a city.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "There are two chairs in the kitchen.",
                    "ua": "Talking about existence in a place."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. In short",
    "items": [
        "<strong>Present Forms</strong> gives you the base for sentences with <strong>am / is / are</strong>.",
        "<strong>Negatives</strong> shows forms with <strong>not</strong> and the short forms <strong>isn't / aren't</strong>.",
        "<strong>Questions and Short Answers</strong> practises inversion with <strong>to be</strong> and short replies.",
        "<strong>There Is / There Are</strong> helps you talk about what exists in a place.",
        "Together, these lessons cover the first A1 block for <strong>to be</strong>."
    ]
}
